Constitution) is being amended, the text of the existing provision will appear in this style type,
additions will appear in this style type, and deletions will appear in this style type.
Additions: Whenever a new statutory provision is being enacted (or a new constitutional
provision adopted), the text of the new provision will appear in this style type. Also, the
word NEW will appear in that style type in the introductory clause of each SECTION that adds
a new provision to the Indiana Code or the Indiana Constitution.
Conflict reconciliation: Text in a statute in this style type or this style type reconciles conflicts
between statutes enacted by the 2025 Regular Session of the General Assembly.
HOUSE BILL No. 1111
A BILL FOR AN ACT to amend the Indiana Code concerning
utilities.
Be it enacted by the General Assembly of the State of Indiana:
1 SECTION 1. IC 8-1-2-4.5 IS ADDED TO THE INDIANA CODE
2 AS A NEW SECTION TO READ AS FOLLOWS [EFFECTIVE JULY
3 1, 2026]: Sec. 4.5. (a) As used in this section, "utility" means a
4 person, however organized, that provides retail electric, natural
5 gas, water, or wastewater service in Indiana to the public for
6 compensation, including the following:
7 (1) A public utility (as defined in section 1(a) of this chapter).
8 (2) A municipally owned utility (as defined in section 1(h) of
9 this chapter).
10 (3) A not-for-profit utility (as defined in section 125(a) of this
11 chapter).
12 (4) A utility owned, operated, or held in trust by a
13 consolidated city.
14 (5) A cooperatively owned corporation.
15 (6) A regional district established under IC 13-26 that
16 provides water service, wastewater service, or both water
17 service and wastewater service.
2026 IN 1111—LS 6353/DI 119

2
1 (7) A conservancy district established under IC 14-33 that
2 provides water service, wastewater service, or both water
3 service and wastewater service.
4 (b) A utility may not charge a customer a reconnection fee to
5 restore terminated service to the customer.
6 (c) The commission shall adopt rules under IC 4-22-2 to
7 implement this section.
8 SECTION 2. IC 8-1-2-121, AS AMENDED BY P.L.181-2006,
9 SECTION 48, IS AMENDED TO READ AS FOLLOWS [EFFECTIVE
10 JULY 1, 2026]: Sec. 121. (a) Notwithstanding any other provision of
11 law, from December 1 through March 15 and from June 21 through
12 September 23 of any year, no an electric or gas utility, including a
13 municipally owned, privately owned, or cooperatively owned utility,
14 shall may not terminate residential electric or gas service for:
15 (1) persons who are eligible for and have applied for assistance
16 from a heating home energy assistance program administered
17 under IC 4-4-33; or
18 (2) residential customers whose residence includes a person
19 who is:
20 (A) sixty-five (65) years of age or older; or
21 (B) sixteen (16) years of age or younger.
22 The commission shall implement procedures to ensure that electric or
23 gas utility service is continued while eligibility for such persons and
24 customers is being determined.
25 (b) Any electric or gas utility, including a municipally owned,
26 privately owned, or cooperatively owned utility, shall provide any
27 residential customer whose account is delinquent an opportunity to
28 enter into a reasonable amortization agreement with such company to
29 pay the delinquent account. Such an amortization agreement must
30 provide the customer with adequate opportunity to apply for and
31 receive the benefits of any available public assistance program. An
32 amortization agreement is subject to amendment on the customer's
33 request if there is a change in the customer's financial circumstances.
34 (c) The commission may establish a reasonable rate of interest
35 which a utility may charge on the unpaid balance of a customer's
36 delinquent bill that may not exceed the rate established by the
37 commission under section 34.5 of this chapter.
38 (d) The commission shall adopt rules under IC 4-22-2 to carry out
39 the provisions of this section.
40 (e) This section does not prohibit an electric or gas utility from
41 terminating residential utility service upon a request of a customer or
42 under the following circumstances:
2026 IN 1111—LS 6353/DI 119

3
1 (1) If a condition dangerous or hazardous to life, physical safety,
2 or property exists.
3 (2) Upon order by any court, the commission, or other duly
4 authorized public authority.
5 (3) If fraudulent or unauthorized use of electricity or gas is
6 detected and the utility has reasonable grounds to believe the
7 affected customer is responsible for such use.
8 (4) If the utility's regulating or measuring equipment has been
9 tampered with and the utility has reasonable grounds to believe
10 that the affected customer is responsible for such tampering.
11 SECTION 3. IC 8-1-2-123 IS ADDED TO THE INDIANA CODE
12 AS A NEW SECTION TO READ AS FOLLOWS [EFFECTIVE JULY
13 1, 2026]: Sec. 123. An electric or gas utility, including a municipally
14 owned, privately owned, or cooperatively owned electric or gas
15 utility, shall:
16 (1) perform a monthly review of all new customer accounts to
17 identify residential customers who are sixty-two (62) years of
18 age or older; and
19 (2) not later than April 1 and October 1 of each year, send to
20 residential customers identified under subdivision (1), by
21 regular mail, information concerning relevant assistance
22 programs for the elderly, including:
23 (A) energy assistance programs;
24 (B) shut off protection programs; and
25 (C) in person assistance programs.
26 SECTION 4. IC 8-1-2-129 IS ADDED TO THE INDIANA CODE
27 AS A NEW SECTION TO READ AS FOLLOWS [EFFECTIVE JULY
28 1, 2026]: Sec. 129. (a) If a residential customer's electric service is
29 interrupted during a billing cycle, a public utility shall provide the
30 residential customer a bill credit for the service interruption, as
31 calculated under subsection (b), on the residential customer's first
32 monthly bill after the interruption has concluded.
33 (b) A bill credit for a service interruption under subsection (a)
34 is equal to:
35 (1) the sum of:
36 (A) five dollars ($5) for the first full hour of the service
37 interruption;
38 (B) seven dollars ($7) for every full hour of the service
39 interruption more than one (1) hour but less than five (5)
40 hours after the start of the service interruption;
41 (C) ten dollars ($10) for every full hour of the service
42 interruption at least five (5) hours but less than twelve (12)
2026 IN 1111—LS 6353/DI 119

4
1 hours after the start of the service interruption;
2 (D) twelve dollars ($12) for every full hour of the service
3 interruption at least twelve (12) hours but less than
4 twenty-four (24) hours after the start of the service
5 interruption;
6 (E) fifteen dollars ($15) for every full hour of the service
7 interruption at least twenty-four (24) hours but less than
8 forty-eight (48) hours after the start of the service
9 interruption;
10 (F) eighteen dollars ($18) for every full hour of the service
11 interruption at least forty-eight (48) hours but less than
12 seventy-two (72) hours after the start of the service
13 interruption; and
14 (G) twenty-five dollars ($25) for every full hour of the
15 service interruption seventy-two (72) hours or more after
16 the start of the service interruption; plus
17 (2) either:
18 (A) one hundred dollars ($100) for the service interruption
19 if four (4) interruptions lasting a full hour or more have
20 occurred in the preceding twelve (12) month period; or
21 (B) two hundred dollars ($200) for the service interruption
22 if five (5) or more interruptions lasting a full hour or more
23 have occurred in the preceding twelve (12) month period.
24 (c) Any bill credits that are:
25 (1) applicable under this section; and
26 (2) in excess of the residential customer's first monthly bill
27 after the interruption has concluded;
28 shall be carried over to subsequent bills until the total credit has
29 been satisfied.
